# Jira Reports in Superset

This guide explains how to deploy ready-made Jira reports in **Apache Superset** 

The reporting architecture is designed so that:

* Jira data is extracted into a database  
* Transformation and prepares analytical tables, if needed  
* All calculations (velocity, time in status, predictability, efficiency, etc.) are done in the data layer  
* Superset is used only for visualization  
* Dashboards can be imported directly from export files

## Getting Jira data into a database

Before Superset can display any reports, Jira data must be extracted and stored in a relational database. Superset is a visualization layer only. All raw data ingestion and transformations must happen upstream.

There are several viable approaches.

### Airbyte option

Airbyte provides a ready-made Jira connector that handles authentication, pagination, incremental sync, and schema evolution automatically. After configuration, it continuously syncs Jira entities such as issues, projects, sprints, and changelogs into a destination database. This approach is ideal for organizations that want a low-maintenance and reliable ingestion layer without building custom pipelines.

Currently, most Jira issue fields, including custom fields, are stored as nested JSON inside a single fields column in the destination database. This means the data is not immediately analytics-ready. Before it can be used for reporting, it must be transformed and normalized into structured columns. This transformation step can be handled by dbt or any other tools.

[https://docs.airbyte.com/integrations/sources/jira](https://docs.airbyte.com/integrations/sources/jira)

### Direct Jira REST API

A custom integration based on the Jira REST API provides full control over data extraction logic and schema design. In this approach, a custom script or ETL pipeline fetches issues, projects, sprint data, and changelog history directly from Jira and loads them into a database.

The main advantage of this approach is that the data can be stored directly in an analytics-ready structure. Instead of keeping complex nested JSON fields, the pipeline can extract only the required attributes, normalize custom fields immediately, and build tables that already match the structure expected by Superset and the dbt analytical layer. This significantly reduces the amount of downstream transformation required.

However, while this method allows precise customization and optimization, it requires engineering resources to manage pagination, rate limits, incremental updates, historical change tracking, and long-term maintenance of the integration.

### Managed ELT Platforms (Fivetran, Stitch, etc.)

Managed ELT platforms provide enterprise-grade Jira connectors with built-in reliability, monitoring, and automatic schema management. These tools simplify operational maintenance and integrate well into existing data platforms. They are typically subscription-based and are most appropriate for organizations that already rely on managed data ingestion services.

### Minimum Required Data

Regardless of the ingestion strategy, the following data must be available in the database:

* Issues  
* Issue changelog  
* Sprints  
* Projects

The changelog is mandatory. Without it, metrics such as time in status, sprint predictability, and velocity accuracy cannot be calculated correctly.

## Transformations and Calculations (Preparing Data for Superset)

Regardless of the ingestion method, the data must be:

* Normalized  
* Structured into relational tables  
* Enriched with calculated metrics  
* Aggregated into reporting-ready datasets

As a best practice, all calculations and business logic should be implemented outside of Superset, within the transformation layer. This approach improves Superset performance, reduces dashboard load time, and ensures consistent, reproducible metrics across reports.

There are multiple ways to implement this layer.

- dbt is a SQL-based transformation framework designed for building reliable analytical models. As example [here](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/tree/main/jira) is the public repo ot the dbt project with transformation of the data fetched by using the airbyte  
- SQL-Only Transformation Layer transformations can be implemented directly in the database  
- Data Warehouse Transformation Tools  
- Python-Based Transformation Pipeline

## Database Required Tables Structure

The structure is intentionally designed around three logical layers:

* Core entities (issues, sprints)  
* Historical tracking (status and sprint changes)  
* Pre-calculated analytical views (velocity, efficiency, time in status, etc.)

![][image1]

Diagram can be found [here](https://dbdocs.io/banderrras/Superset-Jira-Reports-DB-structure?view=relationships)

### Core Tables

### [**issues**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/issues.sql)

Primary key: issue\_id

Required columns:

* issue\_id (bigint, PK)  
* issue\_key (varchar, unique)  
* issue\_type (varchar)  
* summary (varchar)  
* priority (varchar)  
* reporter (varchar)  
* assignee (varchar)  
* status (varchar)  
* created\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* resolved\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* story\_points (double)  
* first\_committed\_sprint\_id (bigint, FK → sprints.sprint\_id)  
* project\_key (varchar)  
* project (varchar)

---

### [**sprints**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/sprints.sql)

Primary key: sprint\_id

Required columns:

* sprint\_id (bigint, PK)  
* name (varchar)  
* original\_name (varchar)  
* state (varchar: future | active | closed)  
* started\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* completed\_at (timestamp with time zone)

---

### [**issue\_sprint\_links**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/issue_sprint_links.sql)

Composite unique key: (issue\_id, sprint\_id)

Required columns:

* issue\_id (bigint, FK → issues.issue\_id)  
* sprint\_id (bigint, FK → sprints.sprint\_id)  
* added\_at (timestamp with time zone)

### Historical Tables

### [**issue\_status\_histories**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/issue_status_histories.sql)

Required columns:

* issue\_id (bigint, FK → issues.issue\_id)  
* issue\_key (varchar)  
* changed\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* from\_status (varchar)  
* to\_status (varchar)

---

### [**issue\_sprint\_histories**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/issue_sprint_histories.sql)

Required columns:

* issue\_id (bigint, FK → issues.issue\_id)  
* issue\_key (varchar)  
* changed\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* from\_string (varchar)  
* to\_string (varchar)  
* from\_id (varchar)  
* to\_id (varchar)

### Analytical Tables

These tables are directly consumed by Superset dashboards.

---

### [**efficiency**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/efficiency.sql)

* sprint\_id (bigint, FK → sprints.sprint\_id)  
* sprint\_name (varchar)  
* started\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* issue\_id (bigint, FK → issues.issue\_id)  
* summary (varchar)  
* project (varchar)  
* metric\_type (varchar: delivered\_story | opened\_bug)

---

### [**opened\_vs\_closed\_bugs**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/opened_vs_closed_bugs.sql)

* sprint\_id (bigint, FK → sprints.sprint\_id)  
* sprint\_name (varchar)  
* issue\_url (varchar)  
* summary (varchar)  
* project (varchar)  
* created\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* resolved\_at (timestamp with time zone)  
* priority (varchar)  
* status (varchar: opened | closed)

---

### [**project\_velocity\_and\_predictability**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/project_velocity_and_predictability.sql)

* sprint\_id (bigint, FK → sprints.sprint\_id)  
* sprint\_name (varchar)  
* issue\_url (varchar)  
* issue\_type (varchar)  
* summary (varchar)  
* project (varchar)  
* status (varchar: committed | delivered)

---

### [**time\_in\_status**](https://github.com/canonical/dbt-jira-data/blob/main/jira/models/marts/issues/time_in_status.sql)

* issue\_url (varchar)  
* sprint\_id (bigint, FK → sprints.sprint\_id)  
* sprint\_name (varchar)  
* issue\_id (bigint, FK → issues.issue\_id)  
* summary (varchar)  
* status (varchar)  
* project (varchar)  
* period\_start (timestamp with time zone)  
* period\_end (timestamp with time zone)  
* seconds\_in\_status (bigint)  
* hours\_in\_status (decimal)

## Superset configuration

1) Create a connection in Superset pointing to your analytics database (the schema built by dbt or other transformation layer).  
2) Retrieve the UUID of the created database connection from the Superset UI, or  
   Via REST API /api/v1/database/ in the browser  
3) Download the Superset YAML export from [https://github.com/canonical/superset\_jira\_reports/tree/main/dashboard\_jira\_reports\_export](https://github.com/canonical/superset_jira_reports/tree/main/dashboard_jira_reports_export) . These files contain dashboards, charts, datasets, and database definitions.  
4) In the database YAML file, replace the existing `uuid` with the UUID obtained previously  
5) In all dataset YAML files:  
   1) Replace `database_uuid` with the new UUID  
   2) Update `schema` if needed (e.g., `dbt_prod`)  
   3) Update `catalog` if required  
6) Zip the modified folder while preserving its structure.  
7) Import it to the superset  
8) Check all dashboards, charts and datasets
